elief about their role and responsibility to the earth; a firm understanding of their sovereign status as a confederacy of independant nations; and their responsibility to maintain those relations for future generations. After more than two centuries of political struggle Haudenosaunee thought has avoided stagnant conservatism and continues to inspire ways to address current social and political realities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIroquois IndiansxEthnic identityxOntario, Southern. 0aIroquois IndiansxHistoryxOntario, Southern. 0aIroquois IndiansxIntellectual lifexOntario, Southern. 0aIroquois IndiansxPolitics and governmentxOntario, Southern. 0aIroquois IndianszOntario, SouthernxEthnic identity. 0aIroquois IndianszOntario, SouthernxHistory. 0aIroquois IndianszOntario, SouthernxIntellectual life. 0aIroquois IndianszOntario, SouthernxPolitics and government. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755468140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554681/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles